By the order of the Chief sanitary doctor of the Akmola region (Kazakhstan), starting March 20, the akims of cities and the regions need to oversee
 - the treatment with the use of detergents and disinfectants of public transport after each course; public transport stops (once a day), public places (sidewalks, parks, squares, etc.);
 - the observance of the sanitary and disinfection regime at the objects of mass stay and life support (public service centres, utility facilities, railway stations, airports, etc.);
  -creation of mobile teams for disinfection treatment of common areas.

On May 11, Prime minister of Kazakhstan announced that the following documents remain valid past the expiration date if it is the date within the period of the state of emergency and 60 days after it:
1) identity documents specified in article 6 of the Law of the Republic of Kazakhstan "On identity documents";
2) driving licenses, including temporary ones and certificates of compulsory technical inspection;
3) permits for the acquisition, storage and carrying of civilian and service weapons and cartridges for them.
The policy is to be enforced retroactively, from March 16 and last until July 9.

On March 16, 2020, the acting head of the administration of Baikonur city (Kazakhstan) declared that all businesses operating on the territory of the city need to observe the following practices:
 - temperature checks of the employees before they come to work; 
 - regularly use bactericidal lamps, air recirculators in working rooms, for air disinfection;
 - perform cleaning every 2 hours, using detergents and disinfectants, special attention to the disinfection of door handles, light switches, railings, contact surfaces (tables, chairs for employees, office equipment), common areas in all rooms;
 - ensure at least a five-day supply of disinfectants;
 - limit business trips and outbound vacations for the employees, and control the return of workers from overseas business trips and vacations from countries where cases of COVID-19 have been registered;
 - inform employees about the need to comply with the rules of personal and public hygiene: regular washing of hands with soap or treatment with skin antiseptics - throughout the working day, after each visit to the toilet;
 - assist workers in ensuring compliance with self-isolation at home for a period of at least 14 days in case of their return from countries that have registered cases of COVID-19.

In Pavlodar region (Kazakhstan), starting March 19, the Chief Sanitary Doctor orders restrictions on the functioning of shopping facilities (shopping centres, hypermarkets, food markets, supermarkets, minimarkets, convenience stores, other retail outlets). To strengthen sanitary and disinfection measures, in particular:
- workday 10 am till 6 pm; 
- baked goods only to be sold in a packaged form;
- sales of packaged food products, with the exception of vegetables and fruits;
- enhanced disinfection regime: every 3 hours, with special disinfectants: treat tables, chairs, escalator handrails, stairs, doors, elevators and floors;
- install thermographers at all existing entrances for constant monitoring of the visitors' temperature;
- visitors should wear masks (in the absence of a mask, provide free distribution of masks);
- distribute reminder pamphlets about COVID-19 prevention;
- install hand sanitizers, use a multifunctional antiseptic substance with a prolonged antimicrobial effect in sanitizers, or provide disposable gloves;
- regular ventilation, airing out of the facilities;
- prevent the formation of queues of more than 5 people, observing the distance between them at least one meter;
- assignment of employees responsible for ensuring compliance with these measures ;
- disinfecting adjacent territories at least once a day.

